<doc id="1208391" wikidata="Q172298" url="?curid=1208391" title="Primary decomposition">
<text>In mathematics, the Lasker–Noether theorem states that every Noetherian ring is a Lasker ring, which means that every ideal can be decomposed as an intersection, called primary decomposition, of finitely many &quot;primary ideals&quot; (which are related to, but not quite the same as, powers of prime ideals). The theorem was first proven by for the special case of polynomial rings and convergent power series rings, and was proven in its full generality by .

The Lasker–Noether theorem is an extension of the fundamental theorem of arithmetic, and more generally the fundamental theorem of finitely generated abelian groups to all Noetherian rings. The theorem plays an important role in algebraic geometry, by asserting that every algebraic set may be uniquely decomposed into a finite union of irreducible components.

It has a straightforward extension to modules stating that every submodule of a finitely generated module over a Noetherian ring is a finite intersection of primary submodules. This contains the case for rings as a special case, considering the ring as a module over itself, so that ideals are submodules. This also generalizes the primary decomposition form of the structure theorem for finitely generated modules over a principal ideal domain, and for the special case of polynomial rings over a field, it generalizes the decomposition of an algebraic set into a finite union of (irreducible) varieties.

The first algorithm for computing primary decompositions for polynomial rings over a field of characteristic 0 was published by Noether&#x27;s student . The decomposition does not hold in general for non-commutative Noetherian rings. Noether gave an example of a non-commutative Noetherian ring with a right ideal that is not an intersection of primary ideals.

==Primary decomposition of an ideal==
Let formula_1 be a Noetherian commutative ring. An ideal formula_2 of formula_1 is called primary if it is a proper ideal and for each pair of elements formula_4 and formula_5 in formula_1 such that formula_7 is in formula_2, either formula_4 or some power of formula_5 is in formula_2; equivalently, every zero-divisor in the quotient formula_12 is nilpotent. The radical of a primary ideal formula_13 is a prime ideal and formula_13 is said to be formula_15-primary for formula_16.

Let formula_2 be an ideal in formula_1. Then formula_2 has an irredundant primary decomposition into primary ideals:

:formula_20.

Irredundancy means:

*Removing any of the formula_21 changes the intersection, i.e. for each formula_22 we have: formula_23.
*The prime ideals formula_24 are all distinct.

Moreover, this decomposition is unique in the two ways:
*The set formula_25 is uniquely determined by formula_2, and
*If formula_27 is a minimal element of the above set, then formula_21 is uniquely determined by formula_2; in fact, formula_21 is the pre-image of formula_31 under the localization map formula_32.
Primary ideals which correspond to non-minimal prime ideals over formula_2 are in general not unique (see an example below). For the existence of the decomposition, see #Primary decomposition from associated primes below.

The elements of formula_25 are called the prime divisors of formula_2 or the primes belonging to formula_2. In the language of module theory, as discussed below, the set formula_25 is also the set of associated primes of the formula_1-module formula_12. Explicitly, that means that there exist elements formula_40 in formula_1 such that
:formula_42

By a way of shortcut, some authors call an associated prime of formula_12 simply an associated prime of formula_2 (note this practice will conflict with the usage in the module theory).
*The minimal elements of formula_25 are the same as the minimal prime ideals containing formula_2 and are called isolated primes.
*The non-minimal elements, on the other hand, are called the embedded primes.

In the case of the ring of integers formula_47, the Lasker–Noether theorem is equivalent to the fundamental theorem of arithmetic. If an integer formula_48 has prime factorization formula_49, then the primary decomposition of the ideal formula_50 generated by formula_48 in formula_47, is

:formula_53

Similarly, in a unique factorization domain, if an element has a prime factorization formula_54 where formula_55 is a unit, then the primary decomposition of the principal ideal generated by formula_56 is 
:formula_57

